Need to do something with https://grok.openbmc.org/xref/openbmc/openbmc/meta-google/recipes-support/rng-tools/rng-tools_%25.bbappend?r=c36a0212?
I did it in the next commit?

This assumes you have a good quality source of entropy in the kernel though. I don't think 5.6 actually did anything to guarantee the initial seed is actually good, it just made /dev/random synonymous with /dev/urandom.

Idk if we can say for platforms without hardware rng actually doing some seeding that they have quality data.

Do we know which platforms don't have a hw-rng driver now?  I thought all the Aspeed ones did and it seems like most of the Nuvoton machines explicitly dropped the rng-tools dependency already.

If you think having rng-tools installed on certain platforms is still a good idea, I'd be fine adding it to meta-aspeed / meta-nuvoton as appropriate (or the equivalent meta-phosphor/dynamic-layers).
@wak - What would you like to see happen here?
I've been looking at it, and it looks like we should be okay now with the latest kernels.
